MARK: released Libchipcard3 2.9.2beta  (2006/09/26)
===========================================================================


2006/09/26: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- fixed RPM file creation: We now ship a separate RPM package with the
  CryptToken plugin (this allows installing Libchipcard2 and Libchipcard3
  in parallel except for the CryptToken plugins)
- removed unneeded files in doc/
- deactivated driver for Cherry keyboard's card reader in 
  doc/chipcardd3.conf.example (should only be activated if there actually *is*
  such a device)

2006/09/25: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- fixed a bug in LCS_Server_DumpState() (unintended recursion)
- fixed a serious memory leak in usbttyscanner.c
- added another method to tell the chipcard daemon about harware changes:
  if in the configuration file the variable "hardwareScanInterval" is set
  to "0" then the server will only scan for hardware upon initial setup.
  After that a scan can be triggered by sending the signal USR2 to the
  daemon (e.g. "killall -USR2 chipcardd3" does the job).
  The default method is to scan every 2 seconds for changes.


===========================================================================
MARK: released first beta of Libchipcard3: 2.9.1beta1  (2006/09/24)
===========================================================================


2006/09/23: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- src/drivers/ifd: introduced a workaround with Kobil Kaan Advanced USB and
  the generic CCID driver: This combination returns alternating ATRs for
  DDV1 cards. The falsely returned ATR is that of a DDV0 card, so if the 
  driver now detects such an ATR it rereads it and only returns the DDV0 ATR 
  if it has been confirmed by the second read.
  This makes the fake-CTAPI now work with MoneyPlex even with a Kobil Kaan
  Advanced USB!
- reverted change of DDV1 ATRs in card description files (the change was
  induced by the strange behaviour of the reader/driver noted above)
- fixed a bug in DDV card code
- fixed a bug in LC_ClientLcc_V_GetNextCard()
- decreased verbosity of KVK service
- create driver and service log folders upon "make install"


2006/09/22: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- src/lib/server/driver: split driver.c into multiple source files to make
  it easier to maintain
- src/drivers: Now there is only one single IFD driver replacing previous
  driver types ccid, ifd and ifdold
- added "static" keyword to most functions in "*_p.h" files thus reducing
  the number of exported symbols
- pcsc code no longer needs PC/SC includes (they aren't available on some
  systems, so we need to declare some stuff directly here)
- implemented the last missing driver functions in slavemanager
- chipcard3-tool now has the option "--start-all" which is used with the
  command "monitor": If this option is given then the monitoring command
  starts all readers before going into monitoring mode


2006/09/21: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- src/lib/server: 
  - merged server and fullserver (only one class now)
  - added slave manager (manages communication with the master server)
    Libchipcard3 has 3 modes now:
      1) standAlone (same as before)
      2) master (like libchipcard2 with enabled remote drivers)
      3) slave
    In slave mode no client connections are accepted. Instead the server
    will connect to a master server (a libchipcard3 server running in master
    mode) and announce all plugged and unplugged readers to the master.
    The master handles a slave just like any other driver. It starts and
    stops the remote readers just like it would do with local readers.
    This new mode replaces the limited support for remote drivers in 
    libchipcard2.
    A usefull scenario is a central gnumed server which also runs the master 
    chipcard3 daemon to which thin clients can connect and report their local
    readers. The master server is then able to use the readers at thin
    clients as they appear (e.g. for the KVK service).
  - created new common class "LCCO_READER" which is now used also outside of
    the device manager
  - chipcard3-tool command "monitor" now shows the date and time of the
    receiption of a notification
- most IPC commands now use a numeric error code instead of "OK" and "ERROR"


2006/09/20: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- "chipcardd3 init" works again (didn't work with Libchipcard2 either since
  some changes in Gwenyhwfar, however, LCC2 is soon to be replaced by LCC3)


2006/09/19: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- implemented card notifications (inserted, removed)
- starcos crypttoken plugin works again
- removed OpenSC stuff (OpenSC is able to use CTAPI drivers, so it can
  use my fake-ctapi driver, too)
- rewrote tutorials


2006/09/16: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- Libchipcard3's current CCID driver is now able to handle IFD3 and IFD2
  lowlevel drivers. Therefore the next release will only contain a single
  IFD driver: ifd3 (which replaces current ccid, ifd and ifdold)


2006/09/15: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- new generic ccid driver (>=1.1.0) now translates feature TLV values 
  (big <-> little endian), so in order to use the feature functions we need to
  translate them, too. 
  Libchipcard3's driver now detects the version of the generic ccid driver
  (it parses the debug messages of the ccid driver and scans for the
   product string. Maybe there is a better way to determine the driver
   name and version?).


2006/09/12: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- fixed a bug in ccid driver: Was checking for feature/control code even
  for APDUs for cards
- added ressource manager type PC/SC to client library.
  This is a big step towards WIN32 compatiblity.


2006/09/11: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- added gcc visibility handling (now Libchipcard only exports symbols which
  are part of the API)


2006/09/08: Martin Preuss<martin@libchipcard.de>
------------------------------------------------
- reimplemented Libchipcard client. Now most code uses a basic set
  of funtions which can also be used with e.g. PC/SC under Windows.
  This is a big step towards being able to run Libchipcard under Windows.
  - defined a common set of functions needed to work with chipcards
  - implemented these basic functions (and extensions) for use against
    a Libchipcard server
  - API cleanup
  - all card implementations now only use the limited subset of functions
    in order to be usable under Windows. Since all card implementations
    already used just a small set of functions this is no restriction.
  - command construction and parsing is now done on the client side, so the
    chipcard server becomes only a ressource manager
  - added command "monitor" to chipcard3-tool: This command shows all
    notifications received from the libchipcard3 ressource manager
  - XML data files are now installed to $PREFIX/share/... instead of 
    $PREFIX/etc/... since they are data files rather than configuration
    files
  - now used ony a single chipcard3-config script instead of separate scripts
    for client and server


